SIMPLE: tablature
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tablature
<hw>Tab"la*ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>tablature</ets> ancient mode of musical notation. See
<er>Table</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>A painting
on a wall or ceiling; a single piece comprehended in one view, and
formed according to one design; hence, a picture in general.</def>
<rj><au>Shaftesbury.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An ancient mode of indicating
musical sounds by letters and other signs instead of by notes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The chimes of bells are so rarely managed that I went up to that
of Sir Nicholas, where I found who played all sorts of compositions from
the <qex>tablature</qex> before him as if he had fingered an organ.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Division into plates or tables
with intervening spaces; <as>as, the <ex>tablature</ex> of the cranial
bones</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Table</ent>⟦br⟧
